articles.headline: Death in Airbnb Rental Raises Liability Questions
articles.snippet: Home rental sites, including HomeAway, do not have the same insurance and safety requirements as hotels, although Airbnb recently improved its coverage.
articles.abstract: Home rental sites, including HomeAway, do not have the same insurance and safety requirements as hotels, although Airbnb recently improved its coverage.
articles.lead_paragraph: There is no better — or sadder — way to explain how Zak Stone’s father died in a vacation rental than how he did himself this week, so this is how he began the essay he wrote for the online magazine Matter.
articles.byline: By Ron Lieber

articles.headline: Irmat, a Mail-Order Pharmacy, Sues OptumRx in Latest Drug-Price Skirmish
articles.snippet: The dispute between Irmat and the pharmacy benefit manager OptumRx is part of a recent flurry of attention being paid to the way name-brand pharmaceuticals are marketed.
articles.abstract: The dispute between Irmat and the pharmacy benefit manager OptumRx is part of a recent flurry of attention being paid to the way name-brand pharmaceuticals are marketed.
articles.lead_paragraph: Irmat Pharmacy on Park Avenue in Manhattan still looks like the neighborhood drugstore it has been since the 1970s.
articles.byline: By Andrew Pollack

articles.headline: Supreme Court to Hear Texas Abortion Law Case
articles.snippet: The justices agreed to hear a challenge to a Texas law that would leave the state with about 10 abortion clinics, down from more than 40.
articles.abstract: The justices agreed to hear a challenge to a Texas law that would leave the state with about 10 abortion clinics, down from more than 40.
articles.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court on Friday agreed to hear its first major abortion case since 2007, one that has the potential to affect millions of women and to revise the constitutional principles governing abortion rights.
articles.byline: By Adam Liptak

articles.headline: Paris Attacks Kill More Than 100, Police Say; Border Controls Tightened
articles.snippet: The Paris area reeled Friday night from a shooting rampage, explosions and mass hostage-taking that President François Hollande called an unprecedented terrorist attack on France.
articles.abstract: The Paris area reeled Friday night from a shooting rampage, explosions and mass hostage-taking that President François Hollande called an unprecedented terrorist attack on France.
articles.lead_paragraph: PARIS — The Paris area reeled Friday night from a shooting rampage, explosions and mass hostage-taking that President François Hollande called an unprecedented terrorist attack on France. His government announced sharply increased border controls and heightened police powers as it mobilized the military in a national emergency.
articles.byline: By Adam Nossiter and Rick Gladstone

articles.headline: An Oil-Soaked Globe as Production Keeps Climbing and Demand Falls
articles.snippet: The renewed collapse in crude prices is helping to again drive down gasoline prices for American drivers, and a surge in production has led to a global stockpile of three billion barrels.
articles.abstract: The renewed collapse in crude prices is helping to again drive down gasoline prices for American drivers, and a surge in production has led to a global stockpile of three billion barrels.
articles.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — Such is the state of the oil industry these days that there is sometimes nowhere to put the oil. Off the coast of Texas, a line of roughly 40 tankers has formed, waiting to unload their crude or, in some cases, for a willing buyer to come along. Similar scenes are playing out off the coasts of Singapore and China and in the Persian Gulf.
articles.byline: By Clifford Krauss

articles.headline: Paris Terror Attacks Leave Awful Realization: Another Massacre
articles.snippet: Ambulances screamed down the boulevards, as a stunned and confused French capital was left to wonder: Why us? Once again?
articles.abstract: Ambulances screamed down the boulevards, as a stunned and confused French capital was left to wonder: Why us? Once again?
articles.lead_paragraph: PARIS — The night was chilly but thick with excitement as the big match between France’s national soccer team and archrival Germany was underway at the national stadium in a northern suburb of Paris. President François Hollande watched with the crowd as the French players pushed the ball across midfield.
articles.byline: By Liz Alderman and Jim Yardley

articles.headline: Defamation Suits Against Cosby Point to Peril of Belittling Accusers
articles.snippet: Bill Cosby’s lawyers were aggressive enough to fend off rumors about his behavior for years. But the tactic may have backfired in the latest accusations against him.
articles.abstract: Bill Cosby’s lawyers were aggressive enough to fend off rumors about his behavior for years. But the tactic may have backfired in the latest accusations against him.
articles.lead_paragraph: In the last 12 months, dozens of women who for years stayed silent or said little have come forward to accuse the entertainer Bill Cosby of sexually assaulting them, only to find that it was too late to sue him on grounds directly related to the accusations, because of the statute of limitations.
articles.byline: By Sydney Ember and Graham Bowley

articles.headline: ‘Scene of Carnage’ Inside Sold-Out Paris Concert Hall
articles.snippet: People attending a show by an American group, Eagles of Death Metal, described sudden terror when gunmen burst into the Bataclan concert hall.
articles.abstract: People attending a show by an American group, Eagles of Death Metal, described sudden terror when gunmen burst into the Bataclan concert hall.
articles.lead_paragraph: PARIS — The band had been playing to the crowd at one of this city’s most popular music venues, the Bataclan, for about an hour. The 150-year-old music hall was sold out for the show by the American group Eagles of Death Metal.
articles.byline: By Adam Nossiter and Andrew Higgins

articles.headline: Three Teams of Coordinated Attackers Carried Out Assault on Paris, Officials Say; Hollande Blames ISIS
articles.snippet: The assault on Paris was carried out by three teams of attackers — including one who traveled to Europe on a Syrian passport along with the flow of migrants — on behalf of ISIS, officials said.
articles.abstract: The assault on Paris was carried out by three teams of attackers — including one who traveled to Europe on a Syrian passport along with the flow of migrants — on behalf of ISIS, officials said.
articles.lead_paragraph: PARIS — Three teams of Islamic State attackers acting in unison carried out the terrorist assault in Paris on Friday night, officials said Saturday, including one assailant who may have traveled to Europe on a Syrian passport along with the flow of migrants.
articles.byline: By Adam Nossiter, Aurelien Breeden and Katrin Bennhold

articles.headline: IBM’s Design-Centered Strategy to Set Free the Squares
articles.snippet: The tech stalwart has been hiring designers by the hundreds, all part of an accelerated approach to product development that is a major departure from the past.
articles.abstract: The tech stalwart has been hiring designers by the hundreds, all part of an accelerated approach to product development that is a major departure from the past.
articles.lead_paragraph: Phil Gilbert is a tall man with a shaved head and wire-rimmed glasses. He typically wears cowboy boots and bluejeans to work — hardly unusual these days, except he’s an executive at IBM, a company that still has a button-down suit-and-tie reputation. And in case you don’t get the message from his wardrobe, there’s a huge black-and-white photograph hanging in his office of a young Bob Dylan, hunched over sheet music, making changes to songs in the “Highway 61 Revisited” album. It’s an image, Mr. Gilbert will tell you, that conveys both a rebel spirit and hard work.
articles.byline: By Steve Lohr

articles.headline: Saks Is Shaking Off Retail Gloom With a Fifth Avenue Face-Lift
articles.snippet: As department stores struggle, Saks is trying to restore its glory with a $250 million renovation of its storied Manhattan flagship.
articles.abstract: As department stores struggle, Saks is trying to restore its glory with a $250 million renovation of its storied Manhattan flagship.
articles.lead_paragraph: Marc Metrick stepped off a freight elevator at Saks Fifth Avenue one recent afternoon and navigated his way past mangled wires and bare concrete beams, his Prada lace-ups crunching on broken glass.
articles.byline: By Hiroko Tabuchi

articles.headline: Attackers in Paris ‘Did Not Give Anybody a Chance’
articles.snippet: Parisians who went out on Friday night to listen to music, watch soccer, or enjoy a meal or drink with friends, quickly became engulfed in a blood-soaked drama.
articles.abstract: Parisians who went out on Friday night to listen to music, watch soccer, or enjoy a meal or drink with friends, quickly became engulfed in a blood-soaked drama.
articles.lead_paragraph: PARIS — François Granier, a wine consultant and rock music fan, thought the concert he was attending Friday night had simply taken a particularly raucous turn.
articles.byline: By Andrew Higgins and Milan Schreuer

articles.headline: Attacker’s Possible Link to Migrant Trail Heightens Security Fears
articles.snippet: French officials revealed that one of the attackers was carrying a Syrian passport, and perhaps may have entered Europe along the migrant trail. Poland moved first to shut the door.
articles.abstract: French officials revealed that one of the attackers was carrying a Syrian passport, and perhaps may have entered Europe along the migrant trail. Poland moved first to shut the door.
articles.lead_paragraph: BERLIN — For months, hundreds of thousands of men, women and children have literally marched their way into Europe, fleeing war, poverty and hunger, arriving in such huge numbers that they set off uncommon displays of compassion — and outright acts of fear.
articles.byline: By Alison Smale and Rick Lyman

articles.headline: Strategy Shift for ISIS: Inflicting Terror in Distant Lands
articles.snippet: The recent violence in Paris and Beirut and the downing of a Russian passenger jet appear to be part of a centrally planned campaign of attacks by an evolving Islamic State.
articles.abstract: The recent violence in Paris and Beirut and the downing of a Russian passenger jet appear to be part of a centrally planned campaign of attacks by an evolving Islamic State.
articles.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Defying Western efforts to confront the Islamic State on the battlefield, the group has evolved in its reach and organizational ability, with increasingly dangerous hubs outside Iraq and Syria and strategies that call for using spectacular acts of violence against civilians.
articles.byline: By Eric Schmitt and David D. Kirkpatrick

articles.headline: After Outcry, Ireland Adjusts Its Corporate Tax Draw
articles.snippet: The country has been accused of acting like a low-tax haven, giving breaks that have attracted international companies. Now Ireland is phasing out some breaks, but adding another.
articles.abstract: The country has been accused of acting like a low-tax haven, giving breaks that have attracted international companies. Now Ireland is phasing out some breaks, but adding another.
articles.lead_paragraph: CORK, Ireland — As lord mayor of this quiet seaside city in southern Ireland, Chris O’Leary seems to have a situation most other local politicians can only dream about.
articles.byline: By Mark Scott

articles.headline: ​Supporting France, Obama Loath to Add Troops to ISIS Fight
articles.snippet: Even as the president searched for ways to step up the war against the terrorist group, White House officials again ruled out introducing substantial numbers of American ground troops.
articles.abstract: Even as the president searched for ways to step up the war against the terrorist group, White House officials again ruled out introducing substantial numbers of American ground troops.
articles.lead_paragraph: ANTALYA, Turkey — For President Obama, the short-term response to the terrorist attacks in Paris was straightforward and relatively easy: The American military and intelligence agencies provided information to help French warplanes bomb Islamic State targets on Sunday in the group’s stronghold in northern Syria.
articles.byline: By Michael D. Shear and Peter Baker

articles.headline: France Strikes ISIS Targets in Syria in Retaliation for Attacks
articles.snippet: The French Defense Ministry said a raid led by 12 French aircraft had destroyed two Islamic State targets in Raqqa, the group’s self-proclaimed capital.
articles.abstract: The French Defense Ministry said a raid led by 12 French aircraft had destroyed two Islamic State targets in Raqqa, the group’s self-proclaimed capital.
articles.lead_paragraph: PARIS — France bombed the Syrian city of Raqqa on Sunday night, its most aggressive strike against the Islamic State group it blames for killing 129 people in a string of terrorist attacks across Paris only two days before.
articles.byline: By Alissa J. Rubin and Anne Barnard

articles.headline: Efforts to Rein In Arbitration Come Under Well-Financed Attack
articles.snippet: As regulators, lawmakers and the Justice Department pushed to restrict arbitration, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and others pushed back.
articles.abstract: As regulators, lawmakers and the Justice Department pushed to restrict arbitration, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and others pushed back.
articles.lead_paragraph: A television ad during the Republican presidential debate last Tuesday depicted pale bureaucrats rubber-stamping the word “DENIED” on the files of frustrated Americans, beneath a red banner of Senator Elizabeth Warren evoking a Communist apparatchik.
articles.byline: By Jessica Silver-Greenberg and Michael Corkery

articles.headline: Blacks Are Challenged to Buy From Black-Owned Businesses to Close Gap
articles.snippet: Blacks spend less money in black-owned businesses than other racial and ethnic groups spend in businesses owned by members of their groups, including Hispanics and Asians.
articles.abstract: Blacks spend less money in black-owned businesses than other racial and ethnic groups spend in businesses owned by members of their groups, including Hispanics and Asians.
articles.lead_paragraph: CHICAGO — Should black people go out of their way to patronize black-owned business?
articles.byline: By Tatiana Walk-Morris

articles.headline: Japan Economy Contracts 0.8%, Returning to Recession
articles.snippet: The economic data was worse than economists expected, and put the country into its fifth recession since the financial crisis of 2008.
articles.abstract: The economic data was worse than economists expected, and put the country into its fifth recession since the financial crisis of 2008.
articles.lead_paragraph: TOKYO — The Japanese economy deteriorated more severely than expected in the third quarter, government data released on Monday showed, extending a downturn into a second consecutive three-month period and putting the country in technical recession.
articles.byline: By Jonathan Soble

articles.headline: Inquiry Finds Mounting Proof of Syria Link to Paris Attacks
articles.snippet: With investigators moving on multiple fronts, there is intense scrutiny on three brothers, living in Belgium, as key suspects in the elaborate plot.
articles.abstract: With investigators moving on multiple fronts, there is intense scrutiny on three brothers, living in Belgium, as key suspects in the elaborate plot.
articles.lead_paragraph: PARIS — On both sides of the Atlantic, the fast-moving investigation into the deadly Paris terrorist attacks steadily accumulated clues on Sunday: a car discovered in the Parisian suburbs with a cache of weapons. Mounting proof of links between the Islamic State in Syria and the attackers. And intense scrutiny on three brothers, living in Belgium, as crucial suspects in the elaborate plot.
articles.byline: By Jim Yardley, Katrin Bennhold, Michael S. Schmidt and Adam Nossiter

articles.headline: Iowa TV Gets Its Close-Up, Enjoying Outsize Influence
articles.snippet: Over the last several years, a wave of consolidation has swept across the industry with station owners trying to put themselves in the path of more of political advertising dollars.
articles.abstract: Over the last several years, a wave of consolidation has swept across the industry with station owners trying to put themselves in the path of more of political advertising dollars.
articles.lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — The news team at the station KCCI buzzed with nervous anticipation here at Drake University on Saturday night, less than two hours before the start of the Democratic candidates’ debate.
articles.byline: By Emily Steel

articles.headline: In Presidential Campaign, It’s Now Terrorism, Not Taxes
articles.snippet: The assault on Paris has thrust national security to the heart of the presidential race, forcing candidates to scramble to address terrorism concerns.
articles.abstract: The assault on Paris has thrust national security to the heart of the presidential race, forcing candidates to scramble to address terrorism concerns.
articles.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Bernie Sanders dispensed with the threat from the Islamic State in two sentences at the start of the Democratic debate before abruptly pivoting to the dangers of a “rigged economy.” Ben Carson struggled to answer a simple question on Sunday about how he would form a coalition to fight the militant group. And Marco Rubio, after pushing out a new video about the “clash of civilizations,” revamped his plans for an important Monday appearance before a group of executives on the assumption that terrorism, not tax rates, would be their most pressing concern.
articles.byline: By Jonathan Martin

articles.headline: After Paris Attacks, Waiting for Shopping and Culture to Come Back to Life
articles.snippet: In other cities hit by terrorist attacks, effects on commerce have been short-lived. Will the French capital — and the broader eurozone — be different?
articles.abstract: In other cities hit by terrorist attacks, effects on commerce have been short-lived. Will the French capital — and the broader eurozone — be different?
articles.lead_paragraph: PARIS — The Christmas market and festive lights had just gone up on the Avenue des Champs-Élysées, and merchants were hoping for a strong retail season, when the weekend’s brutal terrorist attacks cast a pall on Paris.
articles.byline: By David Jolly, Jack Ewing and Doreen Carvajal

articles.headline: Call to Arms in France Amid Hunt for Belgian Suspect in Paris Attacks
articles.snippet: President François Hollande said, “France is at war,” as security forces in France and Belgium zeroed in on a man they call the architect of the assault.
articles.abstract: President François Hollande said, “France is at war,” as security forces in France and Belgium zeroed in on a man they call the architect of the assault.
articles.lead_paragraph: PARIS — President François Hollande of France called on Monday for constitutional amendments to fight potential terrorists at home and for an aggressive effort to “eradicate” the Islamic State abroad.
articles.byline: By Aurelien Breeden, Kimiko de Freytas-Tamura and Katrin Bennhold

articles.headline: Marriott to Buy Starwood Hotels, Creating World’s Largest Hotel Company
articles.snippet: The $12.2 billion deal, expected to close in the middle of next year, would give the combined company more than 5,500 owned or franchised hotels with 1.1 million rooms around the world.
articles.abstract: The $12.2 billion deal, expected to close in the middle of next year, would give the combined company more than 5,500 owned or franchised hotels with 1.1 million rooms around the world.
articles.lead_paragraph: When Marriott International’s $12.2 billion bid for Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide was announced on Monday morning, investors and analysts were surprised.
articles.byline: By Leslie Picker
